'''Benito Antonio Martínez Ocasio''' (born March 10, 1994), known professionally as '''Bad Bunny''', is a Puerto Rican rapper, singer, actor, and record producer.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|author=Timothy Monger|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bad-bunny-mn0003595289/biography|title=Bad Bunny|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=November 15, 2019|archive-date=February 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210215092724/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bad-bunny-mn0003595289/biography|url-status=live}}</ref> Known as the "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King of Latin Trap]]",<ref name="gq.com" /><ref name="GQ">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.gq.com/story/bad-bunny-good-times-profile|title=Good Times With Bad Bunny|last=Herrera|first=Isabelia|magazine=[[GQ]]|date=March 20, 2019|access-date=February 29, 2020|archive-date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307235710/https://www.gq.com/story/bad-bunny-good-times-profile|url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny is the first non-English-language act to become  [[Spotify]]'s [[List of most-streamed artists on Spotify#Most-streamed artists|most streamed artist of the year]].  He holds the second-biggest streaming year of any artist in Spotify history, generating over 18.5&nbsp;billion streams in 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taylor Swift Beats Out Bad Bunny in 2023's Spotify Wrapped |newspaper=The New York Times |date=November 29, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/29/style/spotify-wrapped-taylor-swift-bad-bunny.html |access-date=December 23, 2023 |archive-date=December 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231224043904/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/29/style/spotify-wrapped-taylor-swift-bad-bunny.html |url-status=live |last1=Kircher |first1=Madison Malone }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Drake Congratulates Bad Bunny on Breaking Spotify Streaming Record: 'My Guy Is Moving Different' |url=https://www.complex.com/music/drake-congratulates-bad-bunny-all-time-record-biggest-streaming-year-spotify |access-date=September 11, 2022 |magazine=Complex |archive-date=September 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911013414/https://www.complex.com/music/drake-congratulates-bad-bunny-all-time-record-biggest-streaming-year-spotify |url-status=live}}</ref> As of November 2024, his album ''[[Un Verano Sin Ti]]'' is the most streamed album on Spotify with over 18 billion streams.

Bad Bunny was born and raised in [[Vega Baja, Puerto Rico|Vega Baja]], [[Puerto Rico]]. His 2016 song "Diles" led to a recording contract with Hear This Music, and he went on to release songs such as "[[Soy Peor]]" and collaborate with [[Farruko]], [[Karol G]], [[Ozuna]], and [[J Balvin]].<ref name="gq.com" /> His 2018 single "[[Mia (Bad Bunny song)|Mia]]" (featuring [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]) and appearing on [[Cardi B]]'s single "[[I Like It (Cardi B, Bad Bunny and J Balvin song)|I Like It]]" alongside J Balvin, topped the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 2, 2018 |title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It', With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny/ |access-date=September 11, 2022 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-date=September 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911013351/https://www.billboard.com/pro/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny's debut studio album, ''[[X 100pre]]'' (2018), peaked at number 11 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Zellner |first=Xander |date=January 3, 2019 |title=Bad Bunny Scores First No. 1 On Top Latin Albums Chart With Debut LP 'X 100PRE' |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/bad-bunny-first-no-1-top-latin-albums-chart-x-100pre/ |access-date=September 11, 2022 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-date=September 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911013350/https://www.billboard.com/pro/bad-bunny-first-no-1-top-latin-albums-chart-x-100pre/ |url-status=live}}</ref> while his collaborative album with J Balvin, ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]'' (2019), reached the top-ten.<ref>{{cite news |last=Coscarelli |first=Joe |date=June 28, 2019 |title=How J Balvin and Bad Bunny Made Their Surprise Album, 'Oasis' |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html |access-date=September 11, 2022 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121222924/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html |url-status=live}}</ref> His second solo album, ''[[YHLQMDLG]]'' (2020), became the highest-charting all-Spanish album to appear on the ''Billboard'' 200 at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Roiz |first=Jessica |date=March 1, 2021 |title='YHLQMDLG' Celebrates 1 Year: Here Are 5 Ways Bad Bunny's Album Made History |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg-album-anniversary-9533144/ |access-date=September 11, 2022 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-date=September 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911013413/https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg-album-anniversary-9533144/ |url-status=live}}</ref> It was followed up with the compilation album ''[[Las que no iban a salir]]'' (2020).<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny: LAS QUE NO IBAN A SALIR |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/bad-bunny-las-que-no-iban-a-salir/ |access-date=September 11, 2022 |website=Pitchfork |archive-date=September 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911014852/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/bad-bunny-las-que-no-iban-a-salir/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

{{lang|es|[[El Último Tour Del Mundo]]}} (2020), Bad Bunny's third solo album, became the first all-Spanish language album to top the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny: El Último Tour del Mundo |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo/ |access-date=September 11, 2022 |website=Pitchfork |archive-date=February 14, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210214163737/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Its lead single, "[[Dakiti|Dákiti]]", reached the top-ten of the Hot 100. His fourth solo album, ''[[Un Verano Sin Ti]]'' (2022), spent 13 weeks atop the ''Billboard'' 200 and spawned various commercially successful singles.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Bustios |first=Pamela |date=December 1, 2022 |title=Bad Bunny's 'Un Verano Sin Ti' Is This Year's Top Billboard 200 Album: The Year in Charts |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-un-verano-sin-ti-top-billboard-200-album-year-charts-2022-1235176756/ |access-date=December 1, 2022 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=December 2, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221202030423/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-un-verano-sin-ti-top-billboard-200-album-year-charts-2022-1235176756/ |url-status=live}}</ref> It is the first Spanish-language album to be nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Grein|first=Paul|date=November 15, 2022|title=Beyonce Ties All-Time Grammy Nominations Record|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/beyonce-2023-grammy-nominations-analysis-1235171262/|access-date=November 15, 2022|magazine=Billboard|archive-date=December 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221202172207/https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/beyonce-2023-grammy-nominations-analysis-1235171262/|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout his career, Bad Bunny has earned three [[Grammy Awards]], four [[Latin Grammy Awards]], eight [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], and thirteen [[Lo Nuestro Awards]]. He was crowned Artist of the Year by [[Apple Music]] in 2022.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny is Apple Music's Artist of the Year for 2022 |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2022/11/bad-bunny-is-apple-musics-artist-of-the-year-for-2022/ |access-date=November 9, 2022 |publisher=Apple Newsroom |archive-date=November 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221109141347/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2022/11/bad-bunny-is-apple-musics-artist-of-the-year-for-2022/ |url-status=live}}</ref> {{as of|2024|4}}, Bad Bunny has sold over seven million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vázquez |first1=Román |title=ℹ Bad Bunny: Revelando la Increíble Cantidad de Discos Vendidos en su Carrera ✔️ |url=https://www.sevilladisonante.es/musica-y-espectaculos/cuantos-discos-ha-vendido-bad-bunny-en-toda-su-carrera/ |access-date=June 9, 2024 |date=April 26, 2024 |language=es |archive-date=July 24, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240724211706/https://www.sevilladisonante.es/musica-y-espectaculos/cuantos-discos-ha-vendido-bad-bunny-en-toda-su-carrera/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Outside of music, he performs in [[professional wrestling]]. Bad Bunny began making appearances on [[WWE]] programming in 2021 and made his in-ring debut at [[WrestleMania 37]]. He is a one-time [[WWE 24/7 Championship|WWE 24/7 Champion]] and has wrestled at the [[Royal Rumble (2022)|2022 Royal Rumble]] and the [[Backlash (2023)|2023 Backlash]] [[pay-per-view]] events.

== Early life ==
Benito Antonio Martínez Ocasio was born on March 10, 1994, in the [[Almirante Sur]] barrio of [[Vega Baja, Puerto Rico]], and raised there.<ref name="Billboard">{{cite web|last=Billboard|title=Bad Bunny Talks Growing Up in Vega Baja and Early Music Influences|website=[[YouTube]] |date=October 18, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pheFazCxk00| archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211030/pheFazCxk00| archive-date=2021-10-30|access-date=March 26, 2019}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref name="Avilez">{{cite news|url=http://www.vegabaja.gov.pr/bad-bunny-da-la-mano-en-almirante-sur/|title=Bad Bunny da la mano en su comunidad de Almirante Sur en Vega Baja|last=Avilez|first=Ana|date=September 16, 2017|work=2019 Municipio Autónomo de Vega Baja|access-date=June 28, 2018|language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531212950/http://www.vegabaja.gov.pr/bad-bunny-da-la-mano-en-almirante-sur/|archive-date=May 31, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="gq.com" /> His father, Tito Martínez, was a truck driver, and his mother, Lysaurie Ocasio, is a retired schoolteacher.<ref name="twolatinas">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/two-latinas-created-rolling-stone-s-historic-bad-bunny-cover-n1208081|title=Two Latinas created Rolling Stone's historic Bad Bunny cover, a first for the magazine|work=[[NBC News]]|last=Acevedo|first=Nicole|date=May 15, 2020|access-date=May 15, 2020|archive-date=May 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200516180253/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/two-latinas-created-rolling-stone-s-historic-bad-bunny-cover-n1208081|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="fader">{{cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/08/28/bad-bunny-cover-story-conejo-malo-interview|title=Cover Story: Bad Bunny|work=The Fader|date=August 28, 2018|access-date=November 26, 2019|last=Shepherd|first=Julianne Escobedo|archive-date=November 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106062111/http://www.thefader.com/2018/08/28/bad-bunny-cover-story-conejo-malo-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> His parents had often listened to genres such as [[Salsa music|salsa]], [[Merengue music|merengue]], and [[Sentimental ballad|pop ballads]].<ref name="Billboard"/><ref name="NPR 2019">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/03/681982377/how-bad-bunny-skipped-categories-and-skyrocketed-to-fame|title=How Bad Bunny Skipped Categories And Skyrocketed To Fame|work=NPR|last=Garsd|first=Jasmine|date=January 3, 2019|access-date=May 15, 2020|archive-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103223047/https://www.npr.org/2019/01/03/681982377/how-bad-bunny-skipped-categories-and-skyrocketed-to-fame|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="NPR 2018">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2018/12/24/679179404/bad-bunny-en-espa-ol-el-nuevo-disco-y-sus-influencias|title=Bad Bunny En Español: El Nuevo Disco Y Sus Influencias|website=NPR.org|access-date=December 17, 2019|archive-date=December 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225021753/https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2018/12/24/679179404/bad-bunny-en-espa-ol-el-nuevo-disco-y-sus-influencias|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="gq.com">{{cite news |last1=Chocano |first1=Carina |title=The World's Newest Superhero: Bad Bunny |url=https://www.gq.com/story/bad-bunny-june-cover-profile |website=[[GQ]] |date=May 24, 2022 |access-date=11 September 2022 |archive-date=September 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911033537/https://www.gq.com/story/bad-bunny-june-cover-profile |url-status=live}}</ref> He has two younger brothers, Bernie and Bysael.<ref name="fader"/> He has said, "I wasn't the kid who got involved in the streets. I liked to be at home with my family."<ref name="rscoverstory">{{cite magazine |last=Exposito |first=Suzy |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 14, 2020 |title=Bad Bunny in Captivity |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-cover-story-lockdown-puerto-rico-new-albums-996871/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200514224757/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-cover-story-lockdown-puerto-rico-new-albums-996871/ |archive-date=May 14, 2020 |access-date=May 14, 2020}}</ref>

As a child, he attended church weekly with his devoutly [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] mother and sang in the church choir until age 13. After leaving the choir, he developed an interest in the artists he heard on the radio, particularly [[Daddy Yankee]] and [[Héctor Lavoe]].<ref name="fader"/> His stage name originally came from a time in which he was forced to wear a bunny costume and was angry about it.<ref name="NPR 2019"/>

Speaking about the Puerto Rican music industry, he stated, "I'm from Vega Baja, a small area that's not a metropolis like San Juan where the majority of the genre's artists have come from."<ref name="rolling stone">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bad-bunny-latin-trap-concert-tour-w517474 |title=Bad Bunny: The Four-Billion-Stream Man Leading the Latin Trap Explosion |last=Light |first=Elias |date=April 2, 2018 |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=June 28, 2018 |archive-date=June 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615190547/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bad-bunny-latin-trap-concert-tour-w517474 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

== Music career ==

=== 2013–2017: Early career beginnings ===
He started to write and create his own interpretations at the age of 14,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=2020-05-14|title=Bad Bunny en Cautiverio|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-en-cautiverio-portada-junio-2020-999350/|access-date=2021-08-12|magazine=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|archive-date=May 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200515161600/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/bad-bunny-en-cautiverio-portada-junio-2020-999350/|url-status=live}}</ref> until, in 2013, he began to publish his songs through SoundCloud, including "Get" in 2013, "Tentación" in 2014, "Just let me know" in 2015, among others.<ref>{{cite web|last=CMTV|title=CMTV – Biografía de Bad Bunny|url=https://www.cmtv.com.ar/biografia/show.php?bnid=2498&banda=Bad_Bunny|access-date=2021-08-12|website=CMTV|language=es|archive-date=August 5, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210805145935/https://www.cmtv.com.ar/biografia/show.php?bnid=2498&banda=Bad_Bunny|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, his song "Diles" caught the attention of [[DJ Luian]] from [[SoundCloud]] who signed him to his record label, Hear this Music.<ref name=allmusic/><ref name=":1">{{cite news|url=https://peru21.pe/espectaculos/bad-bunny-ano-trabajaba-supermercado-385993|title=Bad Bunny: "Hace un año trabajaba en un supermercado"|date=November 27, 2017|work=Peru21|access-date=December 2, 2017|language=es|trans-title=Bad Bunny: "A year ago I was working in a supermarket"|archive-date=December 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203013723/https://peru21.pe/espectaculos/bad-bunny-ano-trabajaba-supermercado-385993|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/the-rise-of-bad-bunny-from-superstore-bagger-to-king-of-trap-music-exclusive-111455|title=The Rise of Bad Bunny: From Superstore Bagger to King of Trap Music (Exclusive) &#124; Entertainment Tonight|website=www.etonline.com|date=October 11, 2018 |access-date=March 21, 2021|archive-date=April 13, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413032750/https://www.etonline.com/the-rise-of-bad-bunny-from-superstore-bagger-to-king-of-trap-music-exclusive-111455|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://remezcla.com/features/music/bad-bunny-profile/|title=How Bad Bunny Became the Poster Boy of Trap en Español|work=Remezcla|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-date=October 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201023074232/https://remezcla.com/features/music/bad-bunny-profile/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=changingpop>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/partner/8480619/bad-bunny-how-a-latin-trap-artist-is-changing-the-world-of-pop|title=Bad Bunny: How a Latin Trap Artist Is Changing the World of Pop|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 18, 2018|access-date=May 13, 2020|last=Partridge|first=Kenneth|archive-date=November 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104223510/https://www.billboard.com/articles/partner/8480619/bad-bunny-how-a-latin-trap-artist-is-changing-the-world-of-pop|url-status=live}}</ref> His single "[[Soy Peor]]" reached number 19 on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=insidetrap>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-latin-trap-the-viral-sound-too-hot-for-radio-w501823|title=Inside Latin Trap, the Viral Sound Too Hot for American Radio|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=November 7, 2017|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=June 28, 2018|archive-date=September 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917170456/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-latin-trap-the-viral-sound-too-hot-for-radio-w501823|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bad Bunny's May 2017 collaboration with [[Karol G]], "[[Ahora Me Llama]]", reached number 10 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=hotlatinsongskg>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/karol-g/chart-history/htl/|title=Karol G – Hot Latin Songs Chart History|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=May 5, 2020|archive-date=April 27, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220427172516/https://www.billboard.com/artist/karol-g/chart-history/htl/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=altlatinoahora>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2017/12/21/567803247/alt-latinos-favorites-the-songs-of-2017|title=Alt.Latino's Favorites: The Songs Of 2017|newspaper=NPR.org|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=December 21, 2017|access-date=May 5, 2020|archive-date=December 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221175357/https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2017/12/21/567803247/alt-latinos-favorites-the-songs-of-2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was listed on "Alt.Latino's Favorites: The Songs Of 2017" as one of the best Latin songs of 2017.<ref name=altlatinoahora/>

In the summer of 2017, Bad Bunny signed a booking deal with Cardenas Marketing Network (CMN) for several Latin American countries.<ref name=":0">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7881994/bad-bunny-booking-deal-cmn|title=Bad Bunny Signs Booking Deal With CMN|magazine=Billboard|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102195106/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7881994/bad-bunny-booking-deal-cmn|url-status=live}}</ref> Starting in November 2017, Bad Bunny hosted [[Beats 1]]'s first Spanish-language show, ''Trap Kingz''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8022850/apple-music-beats-1-trap-kingz-bad-bunny-spanish|title=Apple Music's Beats 1 to Launch First Spanish-Language Show, 'Trap Kingz'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-date=November 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106120156/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8022850/apple-music-beats-1-trap-kingz-bad-bunny-spanish|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/bad-bunny/chart-history/htl/|title=Bad Bunny No Metes Cabra Chart History|magazine=Billboard|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-date=December 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203022950/https://www.billboard.com/music/bad-bunny/chart-history/HTL|url-status=live}}</ref> The remix of "[[Te Boté]]" with [[Ozuna]] and [[Nicky Jam]] reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/bad-bunny/chart-history/htl/ |title=Bad Bunny Chart History |magazine=Billboard |access-date=October 11, 2018 |archive-date=December 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203022950/https://www.billboard.com/music/bad-bunny/chart-history/HTL |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2018–2019: Major breakthrough, ''X 100pre'', and ''Oasis'' ===
{{Main|X 100pre{{!}}''X100pre''|Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album){{!}}''Oasis''}}
In May 2018, American rapper [[Cardi B]] released a collaboration with Bad Bunny and J Balvin, "[[I Like It (Cardi B, Bad Bunny and J Balvin song)|I Like It]]".<ref name=":4" /><ref name="I Like It">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny |title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It', With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 2, 2018 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=July 2, 2018 |archive-date=July 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703023911/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny |url-status=live}}</ref> On October 11, 2018, Bad Bunny released "[[Mia (Bad Bunny song)|Mia]]" with [[Drake (musician)|Drake]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/bad-bunny-drake-mia |title=Bad Bunny and Drake Link for New Collab "MIA" |last=Cowen |first=Trace William |website=Complex |publisher=Rich Antoniello |access-date=October 11, 2018 |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012020319/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/bad-bunny-drake-mia |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bad-bunny-drake-mia-video-736308/ |title=Drake Tests His Spanish on New Bad Bunny Single 'Mia' |last=Leight |first=Elias |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=Jann Wenner |access-date=October 11, 2018 |date=October 11, 2018 |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012014540/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bad-bunny-drake-mia-video-736308/ |url-status=live}}</ref> which reached number five on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8481033/kodak-black-zeze-bad-bunny-drake-mia-hot-100-top-5|title=Kodak Black's 'Zeze' & Bad Bunny & Drake's 'Mia' Launch in Billboard Hot 100's Top 5, Maroon 5 Lead For Fifth Week|magazine=Billboard|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=October 22, 2018|access-date=October 23, 2018|archive-date=October 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023001150/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8481033/kodak-black-zeze-bad-bunny-drake-mia-hot-100-top-5|url-status=live}}</ref>

Bad Bunny released his debut album ''[[X 100pre]]'' on December 24, 2018, on Christmas Eve 2018 on Rimas Entertainment.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8491328/bad-bunny-to-drop-debut-x100pre-album-on-christmas-eve-exclusive|title=Bad Bunny to Drop Debut 'X100PRE' Album on Christmas Eve: Exclusive Interview|magazine=Billboard|access-date=June 9, 2019|date=December 23, 2018|archive-date=December 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224012917/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8491328/bad-bunny-to-drop-debut-x100pre-album-on-christmas-eve-exclusive|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], ''X 100pre'' received an average score of 84 based on five reviews.<ref name="metacritic">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/x-100pre/bad-bunny|title=Metacritic Review|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 18, 2019|archive-date=January 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109041349/https://www.metacritic.com/music/x-100pre/bad-bunny|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="TG">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/03/bad-bunny-x-100pre-review-off-kilter-debut-from-puerto-rican-powerhouse/|title=Bad Bunny: X 100PRE review – off-kilter debut from Puerto Rican powerhouse|work=The Guardian|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=January 3, 2019|access-date=March 9, 2019|archive-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103160516/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jan/03/bad-bunny-x-100pre-review-off-kilter-debut-from-puerto-rican-powerhouse/|url-status=live}}</ref> Alexis Petridis of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised Bad Bunny's "off-kilter creativity".<ref name="TG" />

In 2020, ''X 100pre'' was voted 447th in ''Rolling Stone'''s [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/rolling-stone-incluye-rosalia-y-bad-bunny-en-su-lista-de-500-mejores-discos|title=Revista Rolling Stone incluye a Rosalía y Bad Bunny en lista de 500 mejores discos|work=El Universal|date=September 23, 2020|access-date=December 26, 2020|archive-date=October 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201021091429/https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/rolling-stone-incluye-rosalia-y-bad-bunny-en-su-lista-de-500-mejores-discos|url-status=live}}</ref>

On June 28, 2019, Bad Bunny released ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]'', an eight-song collaborative album with J Balvin.<ref name=nytimesoasis>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|title=How J Balvin and Bad Bunny Made Their Surprise Album, 'Oasis'|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 28, 2019|access-date=November 26, 2019|archive-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121222924/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html|url-status=live}}</ref> It peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=oasishot100>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/j-balvin/chart-history/tlp/|title=J Balvin Chart History|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|access-date=November 26, 2019|archive-date=November 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117222500/https://www.billboard.com/artist/j-balvin/chart-history/tlp/|url-status=live}}</ref> and topped the ''Billboard'' US Latin Albums chart.<ref name=oasislatinalbums>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/j-balvin/chart-history/lcm/|title=J Balvin US Latin Albums Chart|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|access-date=November 26, 2019|archive-date=November 18, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211118024154/https://www.billboard.com/artist/j-balvin/chart-history/lcm/|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2019, he joined protests against governor [[Ricardo Rosselló]].<ref name=europetourprotest>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-49013761|title=Bad Bunny stops tour to protest in Puerto Rico|work=BBC|date=July 17, 2019|access-date=May 14, 2020|archive-date=July 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718033126/https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-49013761|url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny and [[Residente]] released "{{lang|es|[[Afilando Los Cuchillos]]}}" ("Sharpening the knives") during the demonstrations.<ref name="Social Movement Soundtrack">{{cite news |title='Afilando Los Cuchillos' Soundtracks Puerto Rico's Social Movement in Real Time |website=NPR.org |date=July 25, 2019 |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2019/07/25/744727518/afilando-los-cuchillos-soundtracks-puerto-rico-s-social-movement-in-real-time |access-date=July 26, 2019 |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725190506/https://www.npr.org/sections/altlatino/2019/07/25/744727518/afilando-los-cuchillos-soundtracks-puerto-rico-s-social-movement-in-real-time |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2020–2021: ''YHLQMDLG'', ''Las que no iban a salir'', and ''El Último Tour Del Mundo'' ===
In February 2020, Bad Bunny was a guest performer at the [[Super Bowl LIV halftime show]], headlined by [[Shakira]] and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bauder |first1=David |title=Jennifer Lopez, Shakira in joyful, exuberant Super Bowl LIV halftime show |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/02/02/jennifer-lopez-shakira-super-bowl-liv-halftime-show-review/ |newspaper=[[The Denver Post]] |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |date=February 3, 2020 |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203035211/https://www.denverpost.com/2020/02/02/jennifer-lopez-shakira-super-bowl-liv-halftime-show-review/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny announced the album ''[[YHLQMDLG]]'' on February 27, 2020, during an appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' and stated that it would be released on [[February 29|Leap Day 2020]], namely February 29.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-announces-new-album-and-performs-on-fallon-watch/|title=Bad Bunny Announces New Album and Performs on Fallon: Watch|last=Hussey|first=Allison|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228232240/https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-announces-new-album-and-performs-on-fallon-watch/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=dropsalbumcnn>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/entertainment/bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg-drop-trnd/index.html|title=Bad Bunny drops new album, 'YHLQMDLG'|last=Asmelash|first=Leah|work=CNN|date=February 29, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229184036/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/entertainment/bad-bunny-yhlqmdlg-drop-trnd/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The album's title stands for "Yo Hago Lo Que Me Da La Gana" (Spanish for "I Do What I Want") and features collaborations with [[Daddy Yankee]], [[Yaviah]], [[Jowell & Randy]], [[Ñengo Flow]], among other artist.<ref name=dropsalbumcnn/><ref name=yhlqmdlgNPR>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/02/811180499/bad-bunny-review-yhlqmdlg-yo-hago-lo-que-me-da-la-gana-la-dificil|title=Bad Bunny Shows Us His Version Of Old-School|work=National Public Radio|last=Gomez Sarmiento|first=Isabella|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302181452/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/02/811180499/bad-bunny-review-yhlqmdlg-yo-hago-lo-que-me-da-la-gana-la-dificil|url-status=live}}</ref>

''YHLQMDLG'' debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming the highest-charting all-Spanish album ever on the chart at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9330424/lil-baby-first-no-1-album|title=Lil Baby Earns First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'My Turn'|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 9, 2020|archive-date=March 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309005428/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9330424/lil-baby-first-no-1-album|url-status=live}}</ref> The album was met with critical acclaim, with the album's musical diversity being praised.<ref name="MC">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/yhlqmdlg/bad-bunny|title=YHLQMDLG by Bad Bunny Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-date=April 10, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410062051/https://www.metacritic.com/music/yhlqmdlg/bad-bunny|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Vete]]" was released as the lead single of the album on November 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/bad-bunny-vete-music-video.html|title=Bad Bunny's Video for His New Breakup Song "Vete" Is a Series of Bad Bunny–Level Flexes|last=Curto|first=Justin|website=Vulture|date=November 21, 2019|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-date=November 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122215831/https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/bad-bunny-vete-music-video.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The second single, "Ignorantes", with Panamanian singer [[Sech (singer)|Sech]] came out on February 14, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cmalone/2020/02/14/bad-bunny-previews-upcoming-album-with-sech-collab-ignorantes/|title=Bad Bunny Previews Upcoming Album With Sech Collab|last=Malone Méndez|first=Chris|website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-date=February 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215175159/https://www.forbes.com/sites/cmalone/2020/02/14/bad-bunny-previews-upcoming-album-with-sech-collab-ignorantes/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="auto1"/> In March 2020, Bad Bunny released the music video for "[[Yo Perreo Sola]]", in which the artist performs in [[Drag (clothing)|drag]].<ref name=dragmakeover>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-drag-transformation-yo-perreo-sola-video-974467/|title=Bad Bunny Gets a Full Drag Makeover in New 'Yo Perreo Sola' Video|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327232949/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-drag-transformation-yo-perreo-sola-video-974467/|url-status=live}}</ref> "Yo Perreo Sola" landed number one on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Latin Airplay]] chart, earning Bad Bunny his ninth No.1 on the chart in just over two years.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=June 3, 2020|title=Bad Bunny Nets Ninth No. 1 on Latin Airplay With 'Yo Perreo Sola'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9396040/bad-bunny-latin-airplay-yo-perreo-sola|access-date=June 4, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-date=June 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200604065559/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9396040/bad-bunny-latin-airplay-yo-perreo-sola|url-status=live}}</ref>

On April 4, 2020, he released the song "En Casita" on SoundCloud, which expressed solidarity towards others in quarantine due to [[COVID-19]] and featured vocals from his girlfriend, Gabriela Berlingeri.<ref name=rsencasita>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-quarantine-song-en-casita-gabriela-978522/|title=Bad Bunny Drops New Quarantine Song 'En Casita'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=April 4, 2020|access-date=May 6, 2020|archive-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404233722/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-quarantine-song-en-casita-gabriela-978522/|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 10, 2020, Bad Bunny released his first compilation ''[[Las que no iban a salir]]'', without previous announcements.<ref name=lqniasbillboard>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9374973/bad-bunny-drops-surprise-new-album-las-que-no-iban-a-salir-stream-it-here|title=Bad Bunny Drops Surprise New Album 'Las Que No Iban a Salir': Stream It Here|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Peters|first=Mitchell|date=May 10, 2020|access-date=May 14, 2020|archive-date=May 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200523212719/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9374973/bad-bunny-drops-surprise-new-album-las-que-no-iban-a-salir-stream-it-here|url-status=live}}</ref> The compilation's title translates to "The Ones that Were Not Going to Come Out" and it contains previously unreleased or unfinished songs.<ref name=lqniashighdebut>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9376803/nav-kehlani-lil-durk-bad-bunny-aiming-for-high-debuts-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title=NAV, Kehlani, Lil Durk & Bad Bunny Aiming for High Debuts on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|magazine=Billboard|date=May 12, 2020|access-date=May 14, 2020|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|archive-date=May 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200514083339/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9376803/nav-kehlani-lil-durk-bad-bunny-aiming-for-high-debuts-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|url-status=live}}</ref> The album features collaborations with [[Don Omar]], [[Yandel]], [[Zion & Lennox]], [[Nicky Jam]], and [[Jhay Cortez]].<ref name="lqniasbillboard" /> Discussing the album's surprise release, Bad Bunny explained, "There was no real meaning behind it. I just thought, 'Damn. What people need is entertainment'{{-"}}.<ref name="rscoverstory" /> Bad Bunny had been filming his supporting role in ''[[Narcos: Mexico]]'' before filming was postponed due to the pandemic.<ref name="rscoverstory" /> It premiered in November 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/narcos-mexico-final-season-trailer-netflix-1235028734/|title='Narcos: Mexico' Makes Way for the Next Generation in Final Season Trailer|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 11, 2021|access-date=November 10, 2021|archive-date=November 10, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211110235640/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/narcos-mexico-final-season-trailer-netflix-1235028734/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In July 2020, he appeared on the first digital cover of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine as the first man to appear on the cover other than the magazine's founder, [[Hugh Hefner]]. The cover was shot by photographer Stillz in [[Miami|Miami, Florida]], and the magazine includes a feature article entitled "Bad Bunny is Not Playing God."<ref name=":2">{{cite web|first=Karina|last=Tsui|title=Bad Bunny makes Playboy history with new cover|url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/bad-bunny-playboy-magazine/index.html|date=July 8, 2020|access-date=July 9, 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|archive-date=July 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200708094057/https://www.cnn.com/style/article/bad-bunny-playboy-magazine/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He also received the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP Latin]] award for Songwriter of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ascap.com/news-events/awards/2020/latin-awards |title=El Premio ASCAP 2020 |website=ASCAP |access-date=July 7, 2019 |archive-date=August 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200808081042/https://www.ascap.com/news-events/awards/2020/latin-awards |url-status=live}}</ref> The following month, his song "Pero Ya No" appeared in an advertisement for politician [[Joe Biden]]'s [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|2020 United States presidential election campaign]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Exposito|first1=Suzy|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-alejandro-fernandez-biden-campaign-ads-1050846/|title=Hear Bad Bunny, Alejandro Fernandez in New Biden Campaign Ads|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 28, 2020|access-date=August 30, 2020|archive-date=August 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200828182601/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-alejandro-fernandez-biden-campaign-ads-1050846/|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 20, 2020, Bad Bunny performed a surprise, live (via his YouTube channel and [[Uforia Audio Network|Uforia]]), free concert from atop a flatbed truck that looked like a subway car going through the streets of New York and ended at Harlem Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/bad-bunny-performs-live-concert-from-flatbed-truck-driving-through-nyc/2627029/|title=Bad Bunny Performs Live Concert From Flatbed Truck Driving Through NYC|website=Nbcnewyork.com|date=September 20, 2020 |access-date=November 30, 2020|archive-date=September 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200923042835/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/bad-bunny-performs-live-concert-from-flatbed-truck-driving-through-nyc/2627029/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Shaffer |first=Claire |title=Bad Bunny to Hold Exclusive Livestream Concert on Uforia |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=September 14, 2020 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-uforia-livestream-concert-1059443/ |access-date=September 21, 2020 |archive-date=September 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200915003520/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-uforia-livestream-concert-1059443/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny energizes New York with surprise mobile concert |website=USA TODAY |date=September 21, 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/entertainment/2020/09/21/bad-bunny-energizes-new-york-surprise-mobile-concert/5859990002/ |access-date=September 22, 2020 |archive-date=September 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200923153246/https://www.usatoday.com/videos/entertainment/2020/09/21/bad-bunny-energizes-new-york-surprise-mobile-concert/5859990002/ |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2020, Bad Bunny released the single "[[Dakiti]]", with [[Jhay Cortez]], which topped the [[Billboard Global 200|''Billboard'' Global 200]] and reached number five on the US Hot 100. The song is included on his third studio album, {{lang|es|[[El Último Tour Del Mundo]]}}, which was released on November 27, 2020, and was described as a personal and ambitious record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/11/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo|title=Bad Bunny Shares New Album 'El Último Tour Del Mundo'|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Cowen|first=Trace William|date=November 27, 2020|access-date=November 27, 2020|archive-date=November 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127050914/https://www.complex.com/music/2020/11/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Caulfield">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9495004/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo-billboard-200-number-one|title=Bad Bunny's 'El Ultimo Tour del Mundo' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart, Is First All-Spanish No. 1 Album|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=December 6, 2020|access-date=December 6, 2020|archive-date=February 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210224213605/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9495004/bad-bunny-el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo-billboard-200-number-one|url-status=live}}</ref> It became the first all-Spanish language album to reach number one on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name="Caulfield" />

Bad Bunny and ''YHLQMDLG'' respectively became [[Spotify]]'s most-streamed artist and album globally in 2020.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9491650/bad-bunny-spotify-wrapped|title=Bad Bunny Is Spotify's Most-Streamed Artist of 2020|magazine=Billboard|author=Aniftos, Rania|date=December 2020|access-date=December 1, 2020|archive-date=December 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201050743/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9491650/bad-bunny-spotify-wrapped|url-status=live}}</ref> It marked the first time a non-English language music artist topped the year-end list,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/streaming/9491694/bad-bunny-spotify-most-streamed-artist-2020|title=Many Billions: Bad Bunny Is Spotify's Most-Streamed Artist of 2020|magazine=Billboard|date=December 2020|access-date=December 12, 2020|archive-date=February 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217145034/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/streaming/9491694/bad-bunny-spotify-most-streamed-artist-2020/|url-status=live}}</ref> with a ''[[The Guardian]]'' article considering him "the world's biggest pop star" for his streaming numbers.<ref name="the guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/dec/04/how-did-bad-bunny-become-the-worlds-biggest-pop-star|title=How did Bad Bunny become the world's biggest pop star?|work=The Guardian|date=December 4, 2020|access-date=December 22, 2020|archive-date=February 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210221064137/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/dec/04/how-did-bad-bunny-become-the-worlds-biggest-pop-star|url-status=live}}</ref> The album received the [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop or Urban Album]] at the [[63rd Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-wins-best-latin-pop-or-urban-album-at-2021-grammys/ |title=Bad Bunny Wins Best Latin Pop or Urban Album at 2021 Grammys |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=March 15, 2021 |access-date=March 15, 2021 |archive-date=January 30, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130214132/https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-wins-best-latin-pop-or-urban-album-at-2021-grammys/ |url-status=live}}</ref> On February 20, 2021, Bad Bunny performed "[[La Noche de Anoche]]" with [[Rosalía (singer)|Rosalía]] and "Te Deseo Lo Mejor" on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', hosted by [[Regé-Jean Page]], as well as appearing in the pre-recorded musical sketches "Loco" and "Sea Shanty".<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Hoffman|first=Jordan|title=Rosalía and Bad Bunny Smolder in 'Saturday Night Live' Appearance|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2021/02/rosalia-and-bad-bunny-smolder-in-saturday-night-live-appearance|access-date=February 26, 2021|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=February 21, 2021|language=en-us|archive-date=June 12, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210612134812/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2021/02/rosalia-and-bad-bunny-smolder-in-saturday-night-live-appearance|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-bad-bunny-sing-with-rosalia-appear-in-sea-shanty-sketch-on-snl-1130929/|title = See Bad Bunny Sing with Rosalía, Appear in Sea Shanty Sketch on 'SNL'|magazine = [[Rolling Stone]]|date = February 21, 2021|access-date = February 26, 2021|archive-date = February 26, 2021|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210226192917/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-bad-bunny-sing-with-rosalia-appear-in-sea-shanty-sketch-on-snl-1130929/|url-status = live}}</ref> On the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, Bad Bunny's next single "[[Yonaguni (song)|Yonaguni]]" became his fourth top 10 entry and first with no accompanying acts.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9586789/bts-butter-number-one-third-week-hot-100|title=BTS' 'Butter' Sticks at No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Bad Bunny's' 'Yonaguni' Debuts at No. 10|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=June 14, 2021|access-date=June 15, 2021|archive-date=June 20, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210620070044/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9586789/bts-butter-number-one-third-week-hot-100|url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny was cast in an upcoming [[David Leitch]]-directed film starring [[Brad Pitt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2021/film/news/bullet-train-first-look-brad-pitt-bad-bunny-1235047141/|title=Brad Pitt, Bad Bunny Slap Each Other Around|work=Variety|date=August 24, 2021|access-date=August 24, 2021|archive-date=January 30, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130214131/https://variety.com/2021/film/news/bullet-train-first-look-brad-pitt-bad-bunny-1235047141/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In July 2021, it was announced that Bad Bunny co-wrote and co-produced the fifth album of Puerto Rican [[Latin pop]] artist [[Tommy Torres]] titled ''[[El Playlist de Anoche]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Griselda|first=Flores|title=Bad Bunny Goes Producer: Latin's Hottest Star Gives Tommy Torres 'Rock Star Attitude'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9604462/bad-bunny-tommy-torres-producers-now-digital-cover-interview|access-date=2021-10-24|magazine=Billboard|date=July 22, 2021|language=en|archive-date=July 23, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210723011831/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9604462/bad-bunny-tommy-torres-producers-now-digital-cover-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny won the most awards at the [[2021 Billboard Latin Music Awards|2021 ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] with ten, including the category Artist of the Year.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9636054/billboard-latin-music-awards-2021-bad-bunny-surprises|title=All the Times Bad Bunny Surprised Us at the 2021 Billboard Latin Music Awards|magazine=Billboard|author=Roiz, Jessica|date=September 24, 2021|access-date=September 27, 2021|archive-date=September 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210927060340/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9636054/billboard-latin-music-awards-2021-bad-bunny-surprises|url-status=live}}</ref> In the following months, he was featured on [[Aventura (band)|Aventura]]'s single "[[Volví]]",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-aventura-volvi-breakdown-music-video/|title=Aventura and Bad Bunny Close Out The Summer (of Touching Again) With "Volvi"|work=[[Remezcla]]|date=August 3, 2021|access-date=October 11, 2021|archive-date=October 11, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211011061835/https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-aventura-volvi-breakdown-music-video/|url-status=live}}</ref> and released "Lo Siento BB:/" with [[Tainy]] and [[Julieta Venegas]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9640709/tainy-bad-bunny-julieta-venegas-lo-siento-bb-interview|title=How Tainy, Bad Bunny & Julieta Venegas Teamed Up For 'Lo Siento BB:/'|magazine=Billboard|author=Flores, Griselda|date=October 5, 2021|access-date=October 12, 2021|archive-date=October 10, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211010230946/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9640709/tainy-bad-bunny-julieta-venegas-lo-siento-bb-interview/|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2021, he appeared on the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s annual list of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Roiz |first1=Jessica |title=Bad Bunny Named One of Time's 100 Most Influential People of 2021: 'He's an Artist, Period' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9630351/bad-bunny-time-100-most-influential-people-2021-j-balvin-essay/ |magazine=Billboard |access-date=November 13, 2021 |language=en |date=September 15, 2021 |archive-date=November 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211113224640/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9630351/bad-bunny-time-100-most-influential-people-2021-j-balvin-essay/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny's 2022 concert tour, El Último Tour del Mundo, has visited the US and Canada indoor arenas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/musica/el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo-2022-la-gira-de-bad-bunny-que-lo-llevara-a-recorrer-estados-unidos-y-canada-nota/|title=El último Tour del Mundo 2022, la gira de Bad Bunny que lo llevará a recorrer Estados Unidos y Canadá|work=El Universo|date=April 12, 2021|language=Spanish|access-date=October 13, 2021|archive-date=October 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211028171249/https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/musica/el-ultimo-tour-del-mundo-2022-la-gira-de-bad-bunny-que-lo-llevara-a-recorrer-estados-unidos-y-canada-nota/|url-status=live}}</ref> He won [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Urban Music Album|Best Urban Music Album]] and [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Rap/Hip Hop Song|Best Rap/Hip Hop Song]] at the [[22nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/files/22nd_annual_latin_grammy_awards_nominations_2021_09_28.pdf|title=THE LATIN ACADEMY OF RECORDING ARTS & SCIENCES, INC. 22nd Annual Latin GRAMMY Awards®|website=[[Latin Recording Academy]]|date=September 28, 2021|accessdate=September 28, 2021|archive-date=September 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210928191647/https://www.latingrammy.com/files/22nd_annual_latin_grammy_awards_nominations_2021_09_28.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''El Último Tour Del Mundo'' won [[Grammy Award for Best Música Urbana Album|Best Música Urbana Album]] at the [[64th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2022-grammys-complete-winners-nominees-nominations-list|title=2022 GRAMMYs Awards Show: Complete Nominations List|website=Grammys.com|date=November 23, 2021|accessdate=November 23, 2021|archive-date=November 25, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211125170413/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2022-grammys-complete-winners-nominees-nominations-list|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2021, it was announced that Bad Bunny became Spotify's most-streamed artist of the year globally, for a second year in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/dec/01/bad-bunny-most-streamed-artist-on-spotify-for-second-year-running|title=Bad Bunny most-streamed artist on Spotify for second year running|work=The Guardian|date=December 2021|access-date=December 1, 2021|archive-date=January 25, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220125021028/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/dec/01/bad-bunny-most-streamed-artist-on-spotify-for-second-year-running|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 24 December 2021, a short film and music video titled ''[[Te Deseo Lo Mejor]]'' was released in collaboration with the creators of ''[[The Simpsons]]''.<ref>{{cite web |date=2021-12-24 |title=Bad Bunny entra en Los Simpson con el video musical 'Te deseo lo mejor' |url=https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/television/bad-bunny-entra-en-los-simpson-con-el-video-musical-te-deseo-lo-mejor-nota/ |access-date=2023-05-07 |website=El Universo |language=es |archive-date=December 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225002624/https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/television/bad-bunny-entra-en-los-simpson-con-el-video-musical-te-deseo-lo-mejor-nota/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The film was directed by [[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Robinson |first=Ellie |date=2021-12-27 |title=Bad Bunny joins The Simpsons in Springfield for new video 'Te Deseo Lo Mejor' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/bad-bunny-joins-the-simpsons-in-springfield-for-new-video-te-deseo-lo-mejor-3126358 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221209035049/https://www.nme.com/news/music/bad-bunny-joins-the-simpsons-in-springfield-for-new-video-te-deseo-lo-mejor-3126358 |archive-date=December 9, 2022 |access-date=2023-05-06 |website=NME |language=en-GB}}</ref> and stars [[Humberto Vélez]], [[Claudia Motta]] and Bad Bunny.<ref>{{cite web |last=Padilla |first=Greta |date=2021-12-24 |title=¡Anda la osa! Bad Bunny entra a 'Los Simpson' para reconciliar a Homero y Marge |url=https://www.sopitas.com/musica/bad-bunny-los-simpson-reconciliar-homero-marge-video-te-deseo-lo-mejor/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016052426/https://www.sopitas.com/musica/bad-bunny-los-simpson-reconciliar-homero-marge-video-te-deseo-lo-mejor/ |archive-date=October 16, 2022 |access-date=2023-05-06 |website=Sopitas.com |language=es-MX}}</ref>

=== 2022–present: ''Un Verano Sin Ti'' and ''Nadie Sabe Lo Que Va a Pasar Mañana'' ===
{{Main|Un Verano Sin Ti{{!}}''Un Verano Sin Ti''|Nadie Sabe Lo Que Va a Pasar Mañana{{!}}''Nadie Sabe Lo Que Va a Pasar Mañana''}}
In January 2022, Bad Bunny was featured in Vogue Magazine for the second time modeling the current season's best bags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny Models The Season's Best Bags |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/bad-bunny-bags |website=Vogue |date=19 January 2022 |access-date=March 8, 2022 |archive-date=March 8, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220308204313/https://www.vogue.com/article/bad-bunny-bags |url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2022, [[Sony Pictures]] announced Bad Bunny as the lead for ''El Muerto'', a film set in [[Sony's Spider-Man Universe]]. The film was originally set to be released on January 12, 2024,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Donnelly |first=Matt |date=2022-04-26 |title=Bad Bunny Unveiled as New Marvel Hero 'El Muerto' for Sony Pictures |url=https://variety.com/2022/film/news/el-muerto-marvel-sony-1235240517/ |access-date=2022-04-27 |website=Variety |language=en-US |archive-date=April 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220426053729/https://variety.com/2022/film/news/el-muerto-marvel-sony-1235240517/ |url-status=live}}</ref> prior to being removed from the release schedule.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Couch |first1=Aaron |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |date=June 21, 2023 |title=Sony Removes Bad Bunny Spider-Man Spinoff 'El Muerto' From Calendar |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/el-muerto-bad-bunny-release-date-1235520812/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230621212748/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/el-muerto-bad-bunny-release-date-1235520812/ |archive-date=June 21, 2023 |access-date=June 21, 2023 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> On May 6, 2022, Bad Bunny released his fourth (fifth overall) studio album ''[[Un Verano Sin Ti]]'' which it became commercially successful as it debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and stood there for thirteen non-consecutive weeks.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-un-verano-sin-ti-billboard-200-chart-debut-1235071183/|title=Bad Bunny's 'Un Verano Sin Ti' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|magazine=Billboard|date=May 15, 2022|access-date=July 15, 2022|archive-date=May 16, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220516235312/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-un-verano-sin-ti-billboard-200-chart-debut-1235071183/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-billboard-200-chart-number-one-thirteen-weeks-un-verano-sin-ti-1235153095/|title=Bad Bunny's 'Un Verano Sin Ti' Ties for Most Weeks at No. 1 in Last 10 Years on Billboard 200|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 9, 2022|access-date=October 10, 2022|archive-date=October 27, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221027211630/https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/bad-bunny-billboard-200-chart-number-one-thirteen-weeks-un-verano-sin-ti-1235153095/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Bad Bunny began his fourth concert tour [[World's Hottest Tour]] on August 5, 2022, set to visit fourteen countries of the American continent.<ref name="Tour">{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/latinpower/musica/2022/01/24/worlds-hottest-tour-bad-bunny-confirmo-su-gira-por-america-latina-y-tocara-en-mas-de-10-ciudades/|title=World's Hottest Tour: Bad Bunny confirmó su gira por América Latina y tocará en más de 10 ciudades|website=Infobae|date=January 24, 2022 |language=es|access-date=January 24, 2022|archive-date=January 24, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220124183207/https://www.infobae.com/latinpower/musica/2022/01/24/worlds-hottest-tour-bad-bunny-confirmo-su-gira-por-america-latina-y-tocara-en-mas-de-10-ciudades/|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 4, 2022, the tour became [[List of highest-grossing concert tours by Latin artists|the highest-grossing tour by a Latin artist]] in history, earning US$232.5 million at the time.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last1=Frankenberg |first1=Eric |date=2022-10-04 |title=Bad Bunny Enters the Record Books With World's Hottest Tour |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/bad-bunny-worlds-hottest-tour-sets-records/ |access-date=2022-10-04 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US |archive-date=October 4, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221004205624/https://www.billboard.com/pro/bad-bunny-worlds-hottest-tour-sets-records/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Bad Bunny received the most nominations (eight) for the 2022 American Music Awards, including his first for artist of the year.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Bad Bunny Leads the 2022 American Music Awards Nominations|url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bad-bunny-leads-the-2022-american-music-awards-nominations-billboard-news/|date=October 13, 2022|access-date=October 13, 2022|magazine=Billboard|archive-date=October 13, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013205409/https://www.billboard.com/video/bad-bunny-leads-the-2022-american-music-awards-nominations-billboard-news/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On May 19, 2023, Bad Bunny released his first solo single of the year titled "[[Where She Goes]]", in which he ventured into [[jersey club]] music. The music video had cameos from [[Frank Ocean]], [[Lil Uzi Vert]], [[Ronaldinho]], and others.<ref>{{cite web |date=2023-05-19 |title=Frank Ocean Makes a Cameo in Bad Bunny's Video for New Song "Where She Goes" |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-shares-video-for-new-song-where-she-goes-watch/ |access-date=2023-05-19 |website=Pitchfork |language=en-US |archive-date=May 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230519004304/https://pitchfork.com/news/bad-bunny-shares-video-for-new-song-where-she-goes-watch/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In an interview with Vanity Fair on September 12, 2023, Bad Bunny revealed that he is no longer involved in the upcoming El Muerto film after its schedule removal. He has also confirmed that he is working on a new album that is planned to come out sometime during the fall, Bad Bunny hinted at the possibility of the upcoming project's sound, confirming that he is "playing around and enjoying myself, letting go. I'm being inspired a lot by the music of the '70s, —across genres, in both Spanish and English, but I'm not sure if this is going to shape my music, generally or just one song,"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2023/09/bad-bunny-on-sex-social-media-and-kendall-jenner | title=Bad Bunny on Sex, Social Media, and Kendall Jenner | website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] | date=September 12, 2023 | access-date=September 15, 2023 | archive-date=September 13, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230913142313/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2023/09/bad-bunny-on-sex-social-media-and-kendall-jenner | url-status=live }}</ref> After weeks of unconfirmed teasers and rumors, Bad Bunny revealed the album's title ''[[Nadie Sabe Lo Que Va a Pasar Mañana]]'', which has 22 tracks and was released on October 13, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-08 |title=After Weeks of Denial, Bad Bunny Confirms New Album Is on the Way |url=https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-confirms-new-album-2023-twitter-tracklist-fuego/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231009103504/https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-confirms-new-album-2023-twitter-tracklist-fuego/ |archive-date=October 9, 2023 |access-date=2023-10-09 |website=Remezcla |language=en-US}}</ref> In May 2024, Bad Bunny co-chaired the annual [[Met Gala]] in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=BadBunnyMetGalaHost>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/wireStory/2024-met-gala-celebrity-chairs-dress-code-107263488|title=Jennifer Lopez, Bad Bunny, Chris Hemsworth and Zendaya to chair 2024 Met Gala|author=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]]|date=February 15, 2024|access-date=February 24, 2024|archive-date=February 24, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240224222324/https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/wireStory/2024-met-gala-celebrity-chairs-dress-code-107263488|url-status=dead}}</ref>

== Artistry ==

=== Musical style and influences ===
