Bad Bunny is considered to be primarily a [[Latin trap]] and [[reggaeton]] artist.<ref name=allmusic/><ref name="Encyclopedia Britannica 1994">{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny - Biography, Albums, Songs, Music, & Facts |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |date=March 10, 1994 |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Bad-Bunny-singer-and-songwriter |access-date=May 20, 2022 |archive-date=April 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220423081150/https://www.britannica.com/biography/Bad-Bunny-singer-and-songwriter |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="GQ"/><ref name="rscoverstory" /> As described in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' article, Bad Bunny sings and raps with a "conversational tone", employing "a low, slurry tone, viscous melodies, and a rapper's cadence."<ref name="rolling stone" /> Throughout the years, Bad Bunny has listed his influences with a wide variety of artists from multiple genres such as [[Héctor Lavoe]], [[Vico C]], [[Romeo Santos]], [[Juan Luis Guerra]], [[Elvis Crespo]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Juan Gabriel]], [[Don Omar]], [[Daddy Yankee]], [[Ivy Queen]], [[Tego Calderón]], [[Wisin & Yandel]], [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]], [[Víctor Manuelle]], and [[Marc Anthony]], amongst many others. He considers himself to be a "music fanatic" which is the reason why he's inspired by so many people.<ref name="Billboard"/><ref name="GQ"/><ref name="gq.com" /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7966054/bad-bunny-biggest-inspirations-daddy-yankee-marc-anthony|title=Bad Bunny Says His Biggest Inspirations Are Daddy Yankee and Marc Anthony|magazine=Billboard|date=September 18, 2017|access-date=September 4, 2018|archive-date=September 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904094855/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7966054/bad-bunny-biggest-inspirations-daddy-yankee-marc-anthony|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="mitu">{{cite news|url=https://wearemitu.com/latidomusic/ricky-martin-behind-the-music-bad-bunny/|title=Exclusive: Bad Bunny Talks Impact Of Ricky Martin Coming Out In 'Behind The Music' Reboot|last=Villa|first=Lucas|publisher=[[Mitú (entertainment)|Mitú]]|access-date=July 30, 2021|date=July 30, 2021|archive-date=July 30, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210730221219/https://wearemitu.com/latidomusic/ricky-martin-behind-the-music-bad-bunny/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="billboard.com">{{cite magazine |last1=Fajardo |first1=Ingrid |title=5 Ways Bad Bunny Pays Tribute to Elvis Crespo's 'Suavemente' in New 'Neverita' Video: Watch |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/bad-bunny-neverita-video-elvis-crespo-suavemente-1235129399/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=4 February 2023 |archive-date=February 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230204042213/https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/bad-bunny-neverita-video-elvis-crespo-suavemente-1235129399/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/latin/8498239/bad-bunny-billboard-cover-story-2019|title=How Bad Bunny Took Over Pop – Singing Exclusively In Spanish|magazine=Billboard|access-date=10 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426075142/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/latin/8498239/bad-bunny-billboard-cover-story-2019|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During an episode of ''[[Behind the Music]]'', he talked about [[Ricky Martin]]'s legacy for Latin music and Latin artists, and how Martin changed the music landscape for future Latin artists.<ref name="mitu"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://genius.com/a/from-ricky-martin-to-fat-joe-how-behind-the-music-impacted-pop-culture|title=From Ricky Martin to Fat Joe: How Behind the Music Impacted Pop Culture|last=Shannon|first=Delisa|publisher=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|access-date=August 28, 2021|date=July 29, 2021|archive-date=August 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828082908/https://genius.com/a/from-ricky-martin-to-fat-joe-how-behind-the-music-impacted-pop-culture|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Behind the Music">{{cite news|url=https://www.paramountplus.com/shows/behind-the-music/video/ZO4uGJWkhO05m4L_R_rHV99sejwXlsTD/behind-the-music-ricky-martin/|title=Watch Behind The Music Season 1 Episode 1_ Ricky Martin – Full show on Paramount Plus|publisher=[[Paramount+]]|access-date=August 28, 2021|date=July 28, 2021|url-access=subscription|archive-date=August 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828080010/https://www.paramountplus.com/shows/behind-the-music/video/ZO4uGJWkhO05m4L_R_rHV99sejwXlsTD/behind-the-music-ricky-martin/|url-status=live}}</ref> In the music video for [[Neverita (song)|Neverita]], Bad Bunny paid homage to the [[Suavemente (Elvis Crespo song)|Suavemente]] music video by Puerto Rican artist [[Elvis Crespo]], leaving a message in the end translated from Spanish as "In honor of the best video of all time". Elvis Crespo later felt honored by his tribute and ended up doing a [[Merengue music|merengue]] version of the song himself in which he performed at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|2022 Latin Billboard Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Alex |title=Bad Bunny Premieres A New 'Neverita' Video |url=https://uproxx.com/music/bad-bunny-neverita-video/ |access-date=August 23, 2022 |work=UPROXX |date=August 23, 2022 |archive-date=August 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220823151603/https://uproxx.com/music/bad-bunny-neverita-video/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="billboard.com"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hernandez |first1=Jeanette |title=WATCH: Elvis Crespo Does Merengue Cover of Bad Bunny's 'Neverita' |url=https://remezcla.com/music/watch-elvis-crespo-does-merengue-cover-of-bad-bunnys-neverita/ |website=[[Remezcla]] |date=August 29, 2022 |access-date=4 February 2023 |archive-date=February 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230204042217/https://remezcla.com/music/watch-elvis-crespo-does-merengue-cover-of-bad-bunnys-neverita/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

Although primarily considered to be a [[Latin trap]] and [[reggaeton]] artist, his music also incorporates various other elements from other genres such as [[Pop music|pop]], [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[Electronic music|electronic]], [[reggae]], [[dancehall]], [[Latin music|Latin]], [[Soul music|soul]], and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]].<ref name=allmusic/><ref name="Encyclopedia Britannica 1994"/><ref name="GQ" /><ref name="rscoverstory" /><ref name="gq.com" /> Some publications have credited him for bringing Latin trap into the mainstream in the English-language music market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/how-bad-bunny-putting-latin-trap-map|title=How Bad Bunny Is Putting Latin Trap On The Map|work=The Recording Academy|date=October 12, 2018|access-date=December 28, 2020|archive-date=January 19, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119075650/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/how-bad-bunny-putting-latin-trap-map|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/how-bad-bunny-brought-latin-trap-to-the-american-mainstream.html|title=How Bad Bunny Brought Latin Trap to the American Mainstreame|work=Vulture|date=January 8, 2019|access-date=December 28, 2020|archive-date=April 13, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413054135/https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/how-bad-bunny-brought-latin-trap-to-the-american-mainstream.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="gq.com" />

According to Timothy Monger of AllMusic, his lyrics "range from humor and pathos to heartbreak and anger (sometimes in the same song)".<ref name=allmusic/> According to ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'', other themes explored in Bad Bunny's music include "self-love, inclusivity, and LGBTQ acceptance".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/bad-bunny-2638705133.html|title=Bad Bunny Just Hits Different|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|last=Jackson|first=Jhoni|date=June 6, 2019|access-date=February 29, 2020|archive-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229051627/https://www.papermag.com/bad-bunny-2638705133.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Public image ==
Vanessa Rosales of [[CNN]] has opined that "in pink, florals and short shorts, Bad Bunny champions a new masculinity".<ref name=newmasculinity>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/bad-bunny-fashion-machismo/index.html|title=In pink, florals and short shorts, Bad Bunny champions a new masculinity|work=CNN|last=Rosales|first=Vanessa|date=November 29, 2019|access-date=May 6, 2020|archive-date=June 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200618185805/https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/bad-bunny-fashion-machismo/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

He has appeared at award shows with manicured, polished, and long fingernails.<ref name="GQ" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2018/08/08/latin-trap-bad-bunny-masculinity|title=Latin Trap Rapper Bad Bunny Is Redefining Masculinity in a Genre Steeped in Machismo|website=WBUR|date=August 8, 2018 |access-date=June 29, 2019|archive-date=June 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629172612/https://www.wbur.org/artery/2018/08/08/latin-trap-bad-bunny-masculinity|url-status=live}}</ref> Ben Beaumont-Thomas of ''The Guardian'' opined in 2020 that Bunny's style influenced fellow Latin artists, who "often now share his highly colorful mashup of [[streetwear]] and [[tailor]]ing."<ref name="the guardian" />

== Personal life ==
===Relationships===
In 2017, while eating at a restaurant with his family after performing at a Zion and Lennox concert, Bad Bunny met jewelry designer Gabriela Berlingeri.<ref name="rscoverstory" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Bad Bunny and Gabriela Berlingeri's Relationship Timeline |url=https://people.com/music/bad-bunny-gabriela-berlingeri-relationship-timeline/ |access-date=2023-10-09 |website=Peoplemag |language=en |archive-date=October 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012181504/https://people.com/music/bad-bunny-gabriela-berlingeri-relationship-timeline/ |url-status=live }}</ref> They soon began collaborating professionally before their relationship became public. The two would go their separate ways in late 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bad Bunny and Gabriela Berlingeri's Relationship Timeline |url=https://people.com/music/bad-bunny-gabriela-berlingeri-relationship-timeline/ |access-date=2023-10-10 |website=People |language=en |archive-date=October 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012181504/https://people.com/music/bad-bunny-gabriela-berlingeri-relationship-timeline/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Bad Bunny began dating model and media star [[Kendall Jenner]] first began to circulate in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kendall Jenner, Bad Bunny Leaving Same Restaurant Amid Dating Rumors |url=https://www.tmz.com/2023/02/19/kendall-jenner-bad-bunny-leaving-restaurant-dating-rumors/ |access-date=2023-10-10 |website=TMZ |date=February 19, 2023 |language=en |archive-date=October 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012181505/https://www.tmz.com/2023/02/19/kendall-jenner-bad-bunny-leaving-restaurant-dating-rumors/ |url-status=live }}</ref>  In September 2023, the two featured together in a shoot for [[Gucci|Gucci's]] Valigeria campaign, one that "explores the intimacy of traveling together."<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Muhammad |first=Latifah |date=2023-10-01 |title=Bad Bunny and Kendall Jenner Get Cozy in Gucci Campaign: Shop the Collection |url=https://www.billboard.com/culture/product-recommendations/bad-bunny-kendall-jenner-gucci-campaign-1235430073/ |access-date=2023-10-10 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US |archive-date=October 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231009141613/https://www.billboard.com/culture/product-recommendations/bad-bunny-kendall-jenner-gucci-campaign-1235430073/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Sexuality ===
In July 2018, Bad Bunny had criticized a nail salon in Asturias, Spain, for refusing to give him service since he was a man; the post led to homophobic comments and questions concerning Bad Bunny's sexuality. Bad Bunny responded to the hateful comments by offering to impregnate the wives of his critics. The post was deleted and Bad Bunny later apologized and deleted his Twitter account.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herrera |first1=Isabelia |date=July 25, 2018 |title=Bad Bunny Deletes Twitter Account After Tweets on Spanish Nail Salon Go Viral |url=https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-manicure-twitter-disappear/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230209203307/https://remezcla.com/music/bad-bunny-manicure-twitter-disappear/ |archive-date=February 9, 2023 |access-date=9 February 2023 |website=[[Remezcla]]}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA" />

In support of LGBT rights, Bad Bunny criticized a tweet by reggaeton artist [[Don Omar]] considered to be homophobic in January 2019.<ref name="donomar">{{cite web |last=Espinoza |first=Joshua |date=January 23, 2019 |title=Don Omar Accused of Making Homophobic Comments Toward Ozuna |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/01/don-omar-homophobic-comments-ozuna |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130205350/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/01/don-omar-homophobic-comments-ozuna |archive-date=January 30, 2022 |access-date=November 26, 2019 |work=Complex}}</ref> During a performance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' in February 2020, he called attention to the murder of transgender woman Alexa Negrón Luciano in Puerto Rico by wearing a shirt with the words "They Killed Alexa. Not a Man in a Skirt", referencing news reports that had [[Transphobia|misgendered]] the victim.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brito |first=Christopher |date=February 28, 2020 |title=Bad Bunny calls attention to the killing of a transgender woman |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bad-bunny-transgender-woman-alexa-negron-luciano-shirt-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130205350/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bad-bunny-transgender-woman-alexa-negron-luciano-shirt-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon/ |archive-date=January 30, 2022 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |work=[[CBS News]]}}</ref><ref name="rscoverstory" /> Ricky Martin has stated that Bad Bunny "has become an icon for the Latin queer community" due to his support of gay and transgender Latinos as well as his embrace of drag culture.<ref name="rscoverstory" /> Bad Bunny was recognized for his [[allyship]] in 2023 by queer advocacy organization [[GLAAD]] when Ricky Martin presented him with the Vanguard Award for allyship at the 34th [[GLAAD Media Award]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-03-31 |title=34th GLAAD Media Awards: Vanguard Award Recipient Bad Bunny Thanks LGBTQ Community For Embracing Him {{!}} GLAAD |url=https://glaad.org/glaad-media-awards-34-vanguard-award-bad-bunny/ |access-date=2023-10-10 |website=glaad.org |language=en-US |archive-date=October 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012181504/https://glaad.org/glaad-media-awards-34-vanguard-award-bad-bunny/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Bad Bunny has also expressed publicly that he views his own sexuality as [[Sexually fluid|fluid]]. In a 2020 interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', he stated, "At the end of the day, I don't know if in 20 years I will like a man. One never knows in life. But at the moment I am heterosexual and I like women."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Linthicum |first1=Kate |date=February 28, 2020 |title=How Bad Bunny broke every rule of Latin pop — and became its biggest and brightest star |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-02-28/bad-bunny-yo-hago-lo-que-me-da-la-gana-new-album |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220829185821/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-02-28/bad-bunny-yo-hago-lo-que-me-da-la-gana-new-album |archive-date=August 29, 2022 |access-date=29 August 2022 |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> At the 2022 [[MTV Video Music Awards]] he kissed a male dancer during his performance of "Tití Me Preguntó".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Netzley |first1=Sara|title=Bad Bunny kisses male backup dancer, takes home VMA for Artist of the Year |url=https://ew.com/mtv-video-music-awards/bad-bunny-kisses-male-backup-dancer-wins-artist-of-the-year-vmas-2022/ |access-date=2023-10-10 |website=EW.com |language=en |archive-date=October 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012181504/https://ew.com/mtv-video-music-awards/bad-bunny-kisses-male-backup-dancer-wins-artist-of-the-year-vmas-2022/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Activism ===
Bad Bunny criticized the lack of humanitarian aid in the wake of [[Hurricane Maria]], which devastated the island of Puerto Rico.<ref name=hurricane>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-fallon-estamos-bien-hurricane-maria-729857/|title=Bad Bunny Makes Powerful TV Debut on 'Fallon,' Dedicates 'Estamos Bien' to Hurricane Maria Victims|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=September 27, 2018|access-date=November 27, 2019|magazine=Rolling Stone|archive-date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513075305/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/bad-bunny-fallon-estamos-bien-hurricane-maria-729857/|url-status=live}}</ref> He established the Good Bunny Foundation, which distributes toys to children living in poverty in Puerto Rico.<ref name="rscoverstory" />

In 2019, he was nominated for [[Telemundo]]'s inaugural {{lang|es|[[Premios Tu Música Urbano]]}}, in the category of "Humanitarian Award of the Year".<ref name="auto">{{cite news |url=https://news.iheart.com/featured/iheartradio-music-awards/content/2019-01-09-2019-iheartradio-music-awards-see-the-full-list-of-nominees/ |title=iHeartRadio Music Award Nominations 2019: Complete List |date=January 9, 2019 |work=iHeartRadio |access-date=January 9, 2019 |archive-date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109205530/https://news.iheart.com/featured/iheartradio-music-awards/content/2019-01-09-2019-iheartradio-music-awards-see-the-full-list-of-nominees/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

On July 22, 2019, Bad Bunny joined artists such as [[Residente]], [[Ricky Martin]], and more than half a million Puerto Ricans in taking the streets and shutting down the [[Puerto Rico Highway 52|Expreso Las Américas]], a major highway also known as the Autopista Luis A. Ferré, in protests against government corruption and demanding [[Telegramgate|Ricardo Rosselló's resignation]] from the office of Governor of Puerto Rico.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/marchadelpueblopuertoricoclamalarenunciadelgobernadorricardorossello-2507138/|title=Marcha del pueblo: Puerto Rico clama la renuncia del gobernador Ricardo Rosselló|date=July 22, 2019|website=El Nuevo Dia|access-date=September 4, 2019|archive-date=October 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015070647/https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/marchadelpueblopuertoricoclamalarenunciadelgobernadorricardorossello-2507138/|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2020, he had not taken a position regarding the [[Puerto Rico statehood movement|Puerto Rican statehood movement]] and had stated that he would prefer to answer at a later time with more clarification.<ref name="rscoverstory" /> He later concluded his answer in January 2021 stating that he would never "want to see Puerto Rico become a State". It was widely understood that he was not necessarily advocating for [[independence movement in Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican independence]], only that he opposed the territory ever becoming the 51st state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad Bunny: "Jamás querría ver a Puerto Rico como un Estado" |url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/entretenimiento/notas/bad-bunny-jamas-querria-ver-a-puerto-rico-como-un-estado/ |website=[[El Nuevo Día]] |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=6 February 2023 |archive-date=February 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230206002204/https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/entretenimiento/notas/bad-bunny-jamas-querria-ver-a-puerto-rico-como-un-estado/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

After a rally held by Republican nominee [[Donald Trump]] at [[Madison Square Garden]] in October 2024 ahead of the [[2024 United States presidential election]], in which comedian [[Tony Hinchcliffe]] compared [[Puerto Rico]] to a "floating island of garbage in the middle of the ocean," Bad Bunny posted several videos on [[Instagram]] of Democratic nominee [[Kamala Harris]] that were critical of Trump.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2024/10/27/us/harris-trump-election/955bb0f0-bc58-502b-8dac-78bf266f21cd |title=The Puerto Rican superstar Bad Bunny today shared on Instagram several videos featuring Kamala Harris making a pitch to Puerto Rican voters. |date=27 October 2024 |last=Ulloa |first=Jazmine |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=27 October 2024}}</ref>

He endorsed [[Juan Dalmau]] of the [[Alianza de País]] party in the [[2024 Puerto Rico gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bad-bunny-endorses-dalmau-election-puerto-rico-rcna178683 |title= Puerto Rico is holding an unprecedented election. Bad Bunny took a major stand. |date=4 November 2024 |last=Acevedo |first=Nicole |work=[[NBC News]] |access-date= 5 November 2024}}</ref>

===Legal issues===
In March 2023, a woman who had been in a relationship with Bad Bunny from 2011 to 2016 filed a US$40&nbsp;million lawsuit against the rapper and his manager for unauthorized usage of a recording of her voice. According to the lawsuit, a 2015 recording of the woman saying "Bad Bunny, baby" was used without her permission in the songs "Pa Ti" and "Dos Mil 16".<ref>{{cite web |date=2023-03-20 |title=Bad Bunny's ex-girlfriend files lawsuit seeking $40M |url=https://apnews.com/article/bad-bunny-lawsuit-baby-girlfriend-ac0d0cadcc8bf8b6553432365234aeae |access-date=2023-03-22 |website=AP NEWS |language=en |archive-date=March 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230322052224/https://apnews.com/article/bad-bunny-lawsuit-baby-girlfriend-ac0d0cadcc8bf8b6553432365234aeae |url-status=live}}</ref>

